In Java, a Set is a collection that:

✅ 1. Cannot contain duplicate elements

If you try to add the same item again, it simply won't be added.

✅ 2. Does NOT preserve order (usually)

Most Set types don't keep elements in the order you inserted them.

Main Set Types in Java

1. HashSet (most common)
- Fast: O(1) average add/remove/contains
- No duplicates
- No order guaranteed

Set<String> s = new HashSet<>();
s.add("apple");
s.add("banana");
s.add("apple");  // ignored

2. LinkedHashSet
- Like HashSet
- Keeps insertion order

Set<Integer> s = new LinkedHashSet<>();
// order preserved

3. TreeSet
- Sorted automatically (ascending)
- Uses a balanced tree
- Slower: O(log n)

Set<Integer> s = new TreeSet<>();
// always sorted

Why use a Set?

Great when you need:
- No duplicates (e.g., unique users, unique IDs)
- Fast lookup (HashSet)
- Sorted unique items (TreeSet)
- Order maintained (LinkedHashSet)

Example use

Set<String> set = new HashSet<>();
set.add("cat");
set.add("dog");
set.add("cat");

System.out.println(set);
// prints [cat, dog] (order may vary)

